post_text: üçé We are excited to share that the USDA Food and Nutrition Service is extending the Summer Food Service Program through Dec 31, 2020, or while funds are available. This means we will be able to provide FREE breakfast and lunch for every student currently enrolled in the Central DeWitt Community School District. Each student will be allowed up to seven free meals per week for breakfast and seven free meals per week for lunch. This includes meals served at school or packaged to-go meals for students who are learning at home. Please read the Parent Q&A sheet for more information: https://www.cd-csd.org/2020/09/12/all-cdcsd-students-will-receive-free-lunch-and-breakfast/ #centraldewittcsd #gosabers #cdhs #cdms #cdis #ekstrand #cdpreschool #stjosephschool

‚ÄºÔ∏èAt the school board meeting held today, August 28, Dr. Dan Peterson announced that Central DeWitt Community School District will extend the Hybrid Model through Friday, September 18. This means students will continue attending school at 50% capacity on assigned Group A and Group B days. Please see the schedule for the next three weeks below or click here: https://www.cd-csd.org/hybrid-model-schedule/.

This decision was based on current COVID-19 numbers in Clinton County and our desire to continue keeping our students and staff as safe as possible. Students will return to 100% in-person learning on Monday, Sept. 21, however, this is subject to change depending on COVID-19 conditions at that time. Thank you for your continued support and cooperation!

üåç‚úàÔ∏è LOOKING FOR SOME ADVENTURE? There is still time to join our local Adventure Crew on their trip to Portugal and Spain this Summer in late June. Because of the pandemic, this trip was postponed until Summer 2021 so there is still time to register new travelers. This trip is currently $3875 for a 12-day tour ($4475 for adults).

We will also be visiting the United Kingdom in the Summer of 2022, touring through Ireland, Scotland and England. This trip is currently $4035 for an 11-day tour ($4585 for adults) but there is a $300 discount for early enrollment that will last until Sunday, September 13th, 2020.

There will be a parent/student meeting in the HS/MS library on Tuesday, September 1st at 7 pm. Interested participants should RSVP at the following link: bit.ly/2Q7McE8 If you cannot attend but still want more information, you can RSVP and select ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt make it‚Äù or you can also contact Mr. Mercado at eddie.mercado@cd-csd.org.

shared_text:
Central Dewitt High School Robotics
July 27 at 7:08 PM ¬∑

Bridge design contest update!!
Kids k-8 in the Central Dewitt Community School district are invited to participate.
Participants will receive a bridge building kit and build a bridge that can hold the most weight. This Friday, July 31st from 4-6pm participants can pick up their bridge kits. On Friday, August 14th from 4-6pm and Saturday, August 15th 10am-12pm participants will drop off their bridges and can watch us test them! Testing will be like a drive through. After testing has concluded we will put together a video containing all of the bridges and the results of the contest! The video will be posted shortly after testing. If pick up or drop off/testing doesn‚Äôt not work please contact us for other arrangements. We look forward to this fun contest and wish the best of luck to our participants!

post_text: In an article published in the DeWitt Observer, it was announced that there will not be in-town bus routes for the 2020-2021 school year. We‚Äôd like to clarify that this decision has not been made. It was only one of many considerations the Central DeWitt Community School District had looked at to support social distancing for our students and help protect our bus drivers. Please know that any changes to the structure of our transportation or school day will always be communicated with our Saber family before the general public. Since the article was published there have been other developments from Governor Reynolds and the Department of Education that have changed plans we shared and decisions that were previously made. Tomorrow we will be sharing these updates as well as other important information about our Return to Learn Plan with parents and students.

post_text: ATTENTION Central Dewitt athletes and parents: If you are an athlete entering freshman or junior year at Central Dewitt, you need to have a pre-concussion screening done by Brent Yotty, our athletic trainer. In order to make an appointment to have this screening done, you need to contact Genesis Physical Therapy in Dewitt at 563-659-4265. Please let reception know you want to schedule a pre-concussion screening with Brent and they will find a time slot available. Also note, if screening at Genesis, you will be required to wear a mask at this time. Brent will also be conducting these screenings in August, but those will be on a first come, first serve basis and may fill up quickly.

post_text: Parents of Softball and Baseball players, be looking for an email with an attached information letter that covers guidelines that will be required from the Governor, Department of Education, IHSAA/IGHSAU and Clinton County Health Department with the opening of baseball and softball seasons. Please read though everything and email Coach Kreiter at kurt.kreiter@cd-csd.org if you have any questions or concerns. Mr. Birt, our new AD, will be organizing an in-person parent meeting for all softball and baseball parents for next Wednesday, June 3 at 5:30. That will take place on the football home bleachers, which will give everyone an opportunity to practice social distancing, that will be part of the requirements for games this summer. There will also be an attached a permission slip for athletes (under 18) and a waiver form (over 18) if your athlete did not receive one in the last few days. This will be required to be signed and turned in before they are allowed to practice. Coach Kreiter

May 27 at 2:45 PM ¬∑

We are excited to announce that six schools have been selected for the University of Iowa College of Engineering Femineer Adopt-a-School Program. Teachers will be training this fall to bring the program to their schools. Stay tuned this week as we introduce all six schools.

Congratulations to teacher Terri Smith of Central DeWitt Community School District! Terri received the Femineer Adopt-a-School award last year to teach Femineer Creative Robotics at Central DeWitt Middle School STEM during the 2019-2020 school year. She has also has been awarded the Femineer Adopt-a-School this year to bring Femineer Wearable Technology to Central DeWitt for the 2020 - 2021 academic year.

Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering San Diego State University Schneider-Electric ACT Student Alliant Energy HR Green, Inc. Southeast Iowa STEM Region University of Iowa Outreach & Engagement

post_text:
ATTENTION STUDENTS: We are very sad to share that we have to cancel Central DeWitt's prom. For more information, please read the letter from Mr. Pickup.

Dear Central DeWitt Students,

Due to current guidelines to prevent the spread of the coronavirus and to help diminish the number of COVID-19 cases, it is with great disappointment that I have to inform you that the Senior Prom is cancelled.

This decision was not made lightly. I know you were looking forward to celebrating at prom; however, this is the right thing to do regarding student and staff safety.

Central DeWitt High School remains committed to ensuring the health and safety of our students, staff, and community.

Again, I apologize for the cancellation, and wish circumstances could be different.

Sincerely,
George Pickup
High School Principal

Good morning! It's Graduation Day!

Our plans for the Class of 2020 Graduation are coming to fruition this morning! It won't be long and we'll have our seniors and their families arriving! Reminder, the parking lot opens at 2:00 this afternoon, and you can only access the lot from 11th Street. For those that would like to view our graduation ceremony, other than the seniors and their families that will be attending, we will have a Live Stream going, beginning at 2:30. Please feel free to join us online and share the link with others! The School District's YouTube Channel can be found at the following link: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCBHEyngG7ReFgrzgOZeby3g

Rain or shine, we'll be sending our seniors out with a high quality graduation ceremony!

Sincerely,

Dr. Dan Peterson, Superintendent

post_text: Congratulations to senior artist Maggie Borota who was awarded the Lillian L. Brand Scholarship, one of four prestigious Brand Boeshaar Scholarships given through the Figge Art Museum! The Brand Boeshaar Scholarship Program awards up to four scholarships annually to Iowa/Illinois area students who wish to earn a degree in Fine Art, Graphic Design, or Art Education at a college or university. The scholarship is awarded based on a student portfolio, transcript, and application. Each scholarship is $3000 for the first academic year, with renewals for three subsequent years up to a total of $12,000. Outstanding work, Maggie!

post_text: ‚ÄºÔ∏è With the district‚Äôs move to online learning, the high school Student Council will hold elections virtually this year! The Student Council is a leadership club that serves as the main voice for the student body, provides civic services to various communities, and helps spread school spirit by planning events such as Homecoming. To apply, students must complete the application, email ten student thumbs-up images from supporters to advisor Mrs. Viel, at carrie.viel@cd-csd.org, and have two completed teacher recommendation forms; all forms must be submitted by Friday, May 8. Links to all required documents are available through student email. Elections will be held May 11-13.

Giving our seniors the commencement celebration they‚Äôve worked so hard for is our priority but so is the health and safety of those involved. Because of that, commencement will be a privately-held event for graduates and their immediate family only. It will take place on May 17th at 3 p.m. The public will not be allowed to attend however it will be streamed live on YouTube.

The ceremony will be followed by a parade through town where we encourage the community to cheer and wave at our graduates from the safety of their own porches. We will share the route closer to the event. We appreciate everyone‚Äôs cooperation to make sure we comply with state regulations and allow our graduates a chance to walk across the stage.

Seniors there will be a Zoom meeting on Tuesday, May 5th at 4:30 p.m. where more information will be shared.

post_text:
Thank you to United Way of Clinton County, Iowa for providing extra funding so our Nutrition Department was able to continue providing meals for our students!

‚ÄúI would like to take this time to thank the United Way for their generous support by providing us with funding for extra supplies during this Covid-19 pandemic. United Way stepped in and helped us take care of the cost of extras like plastic and paper bags, disposable containers, foil wrappers, and sandwich bags. They provided us with the proper funds to supply the items we do not typically use during a normal serving day at Central DeWitt Community School District. The community has been grateful during this crisis and some of that is due to United Way's generosity. It has helped ease that burden to make sure we could still feed our kids. So, again thank you to United Way for your loving donation during this trying time.‚Äù

Dede Wagener, Nutrition Director
Central DeWitt Community School District

post_text: As you may have heard, Gov. Reynolds announced schools will be closed through the end of the school year. At this time our administrative team is working through the new information as well as receiving guidance from the Department of Education. We will relay additional information as soon as it becomes available. There are a lot of decisions to be made regarding the remainder of the year. Thank you everyone for your patience and understanding as we all work through this together!

post_text: If you've ever thought it would be cool to see your artwork turned into a sticker that would be used by many people, then now is your chance! post_text: We are sad to announce the choir concert scheduled for Tuesday, March 17 and the spring play scheduled for April 3rd and 4th have been cancelled. This decision was made based on recommendations by the Iowa Department of Health not to hold events that would result in the gathering of 250 or more people. We know students, faculty, and staff have put a lot of time and effort into these performances so this decision was not made lightly. Thank you for understanding and if alternative arrangements are made we will let you know!

post_text: The Visiting Chef Series had students getting creative with their platings of homemade hummus and learning all about owning and operating a restaurant. Tristan Faville, co-owner, operator, and chef of Chez Lin & Rays in Essex, NY, shared her experiences and a few of her recipes in the three-hour class. They made ratatouille, hummus, a kale and roasted butternut squash salad with pecan dressing, and Toll House Pie ‚Äì all dishes served at her restaurant. Faville is currently completing a Dietetic Internship through Iowa State University to become a registered dietician. Thank you Chef Faville for sharing your knowledge and time with our students! #gosabers #centraldewittsd #visitingchefseries #instructorvalbetz #centraldewittfcs

post_text: Society for American Military Engineers (SAME) in collaboration with the military services, offers a series of week long, STEM Engineering & Construction Camps designed for high school students who excel in math, science, and technology courses and are interested in pursuing engineering, architecture, or related fields in college. Each camp has their unique curriculum, with the common thread being: challenging environment, hands-on activities, mentors who are young engineers, and long term resources for alumni. The Rock Island Post SAME is still looking for campers to sponsor and will cover all registration fees and up to 1/2 of the travel costs for each camper. The application deadline is March 16th, 2020.

post_text: The CDHS Instrumental program will be presenting a concert on Sunday March 8th at 7pm in the CDPAC. The band program splits into two concert bands during the second semester. The Concert (9th) Band will perform Claude T. Smith's "Variations on an English Folk Song," "Flourish for Wind Band" by Ralph Vaughn WIlliams, Frank Ticheli's "Earth Song," Arthur Frackenpohl's concert march "Assembly March," and will conclude their portion with Robert W. Smith's "Red." The Symphonic (10th-12th) Band will perform Jack Stamp's arrangement of "The Star-Spangled Banner," Thom Ritter George's multi-movement work "First Suite in F," Aaron Perrine's "Inner Sanctum," Jan Van Der Roost's concert march "Orion," and the concert will conclude with Robert W. Smith's "Paradiso." The Concert Bands are led by Director of High School Bands, Mr. Josh Greubel. #gosabers #centraldewitthighschool ##centraldewittconcertband #centraldewitsymphonicband #musicinourschoolsmonth #centraldewittsd

Announcing the Central DeWitt Hall of Fame Class of 2020:

*Leah (Berst) Washmon - 1979
3rd Place State Golf, 5X HS State Golf Champion Coach, First Female on North Texas PGA Board

*Dr. Donna Helble - 1967
Professor Emerita of Winona State University, Professional and Community Leader

*Casey Kreiter - 2009
Pro-Bowl Broncos Long Snapper, Hawkeye Captain/All-Big Ten, FB All-State-WR State 6th Place

*Liz (Rumann) Mathis - 1976
Iowa State Senator (2001-Present), Chief Community Officer for Four Oaks, KWWL News Anchor

*Justin Petersen - 2001
Wrestling Wins Leader, 3X Conference Champion, 3X State Qualifier, 3X Academic All-State

*Ryan Scheckel - 1997
6X HS State Track, 2X College National Track Meet, College XC/Track & Field Coach of the Year

*Boys Track - 2009
3A State Team Champions

Congratulations to our Inductees! Once we have our fall football schedule we will be able to set the date for Homecoming, the HC Parade and HOF Ceremony. Please keep sending your nomination forms for future inductees.

As we have had a large turnover in classroom furniture this year, we have a lot that we need to move to a new home. We thought it would be better to make it available to those that live in our District, rather than scrapping or trying to sell it. I have attached several pictures of the furniture that is available at our Maintenance Shop at 305 East 10th Street. It is free to those that live within our school district, first come - first serve, no reserving. It's already disappearing, even before we announced it was available, so if you'd like any of this furniture, you will want to move quickly. There will be additional furniture available next week that will be coming out of our Intermediate School.
Dr. Dan Peterson, Superintendent

shared_text:
Staci Mercado
February 27 at 7:51 PM ¬∑

Facebook Friends and Family, I need your help:

On Thursday, April 30, from 8-10 a.m., our high school is hosting a two-hour student conference intended to raise awareness about preserving the Earth and appreciating nature. We are looking for presenters for two 40-minute breakout sessions. Students will be able to choose which sessions they attend. Our goal is to provide students with actionable ideas for a sustainable future.

We have many individuals and organizations on board already but need to find more people willing to share their expertise.

So far our presenters are touching upon the following topics:

River clean-up efforts (Living Lands and Waters)
The importance of youth voice for environmental action
Solar energy
Gardening
Wild edibles
Bioremediation (soil health)
Spiritual connection with nature
Composting
Cover crops

If you have any ideas, please let me know. Thank you!

Composting
Cover crops

If you have any ideas, please let me know. Thank you!

The Scribbler's feature of the week is "How Dare You" by Crystal Burke, illustrated by Hannah Brogden. Adults should help prepare young people for the real world and encourage them to become the best they can be. This poem is inspired by Crystal's experiences with less than admirable mentors.

Our most accomplished author to date, Crystal Burke has published many pieces in the last three years. If you would like to read more of Crystal's work, check out her tribute to her father in "Best Friend" and her mother in "Cinnamon Roll Day."
Click here to read Crystal's works: https://www.cdhsscribbler.com/copy-of-a-night-out-with-jeffrey-da-2

post_text: Mrs. Craddick‚Äôs 7th grade students are reading "A Long Walk to Water," a novel about a young girl Nya who walks four miles round trip each day to get water for her family, and Salva, one of the Lost Boys of Sudan. To simulate Nya's journey, students wore weighted vests and carried 40 pound jugs of water four laps around the Central DeWitt Performing Arts Center, up and down hill and up and down steps. It gave them a sense of the difficulty of her daily journey. #gosabers #centraldewittmiddleschool #interactivelearning #centraldewittsd

post_text: Students, teachers, and administrators had the opportunity to meet with Lieutenant Governor Adam Gregg today to discuss the future of the Iowa Workforce and how our schools are helping guide career paths. Gregg was shown the house that students, along with the help of local contractors, electricians, and others, have been renovating as part of a high school course called Building Trades. Students who are accepted into this course acquire basic knowledge and principles of carpentry, masonry, concrete finishing, electrical work, HVAC, plumbing, and more. #gosabers #centraldewitthighschool #centraldewittsd #centraldewittbuildingtrades #dewittchamberanddevelopment
shared_text:
DeWitt Chamber & Development Co. added 16 new photos to the album: Lt. Governor Adam Gregg's Visit ‚Äî with Lieutenant Governor Adam Gregg and Central DeWitt Community School District in DeWitt, Iowa.
January 30 at 12:17 PM ¬∑ DeWitt, IA ¬∑

Check out photos from our visit with Lieutenant Governor Adam Gregg! Some students and administrators from Central DeWitt High School showed off and shared information about their Building and Trades Program, the flip house they are currently working on and how programs like this influence the paths of the students which eventually leads to a stronger workforce.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Finger Puppet Mafia! As part of the FIRST Tech Challenge, 22 teams from all over eastern Iowa competed on Saturday, Jan. 25th at Central DeWitt High School. Twelve teams earned advancement and will continue their competitive season with the next round being held at Iowa City Regina on Feb. 15th. Central DeWitt's robotics team was among those 12 teams and advanced by virtue of finishing 3rd in the Inspire award voting (for best overall team) and also winning the Collins Aerospace Innovate Award.

Teams that move past the next tournament will earn an invitation to the Iowa State Championship being held February 28-29 in Cedar Rapids. #gosabers #centraldewittsd #fingerpuppetmafia #FIRSTTechChallenge

Congratulations to Central DeWitt senior and FFA member Heather Cernek for being named a candidate for the U.S. Presidential Scholar Award for 2020 in the area of Career and Technical Education!

The Presidential Scholar Award is meant to recognize and honor our nation‚Äôs most distinguished graduating high school seniors. The CTE based award is given to those who have demonstrated outstanding scholarship, ability, and accomplishment in Career and Technical Education. Only five students in each state are selected for nomination. In total, 161 students are chosen for the award. #gosabers #centraldewittsd #centraldewitthighschool #centraldewittffa

‚ÄúFor anybody that will be using facilities today and for Monday morning the lots and sidewalks still have ice and snow froze on them. .
From Keith Walker, Director of Operations

post_text: Congratulations to senior Sicily Nissen on qualifying for the Biliteracy Seal! Sicily recently demonstrated her proficiency in Spanish with her high score on the AAPL Assessment. Sicily was persistent in her quest for this achievement and only the second student to earn this honor since the beginning of this program two years ago. The Seal of Biliteracy is given "In recognition of students who have studied and attained proficiency in two or more languages by high school graduation". #gosabers #biliteracyseal #centraldewitthighschool #centraldewitt

shared_text:
Central DeWitt High School Art
January 7 at 2:08 PM ¬∑

The Figge has selected Lauryn Ginter as the winner of the 2019 Figge Factory T-Shirt Design Contest. They loved her succulent and cactus drawing and thought it would make a great shirt. Lauryn wins $100, a family membership to the museum, a framed copy of her drawing, and screenprinting party for her and 3 friends. Her design will also be printed on shirts that will be sold in the Figge museum store! We are so proud of her accomplishment and artistic talent! Lauryn went up against 85 entries from Quad City area schools. Check out her design below!
Congratulations Lauryn!

shared_text:
Zane Satre Local 4 News is with Zane Satre at Central DeWitt Community School District.
December 12, 2019 at 5:35 PM ¬∑ DeWitt, IA ¬∑

post_text: Students who participated in the Visiting Chef Series last week were transported to Italy by Kendra Smith who attends the Kirkwood Community College culinary program and works at Cobble Hill restaurant in Cedar Rapids. Student had the opportunity to make pasta from scratch, enjoy homemade marinara sauce and learn how to make tiramisu. Smith who spent two separate months in Italy learning the traditions and secrets behind Italian cooking shared her knowledge and experience with the students during the three-hour, hands-on session. The Visiting Chef Series is hosted by Val Betz, Family and Consumer Sciences instructor. #gosabers #centraldewittsabers #homemadepasta #centraldewittsd #centraldewittfamilyandconsumersciences #centraldewittvisitingchefseries

post_text: Congratulations to Central DeWitt student Benen Greubel who was the only baritone selected from all of Northeast Iowa for the All-Iowa 8th Grade Honor Band! This is the highest honor a band student can achieve. Benen will represent Central DeWitt at the state level in May. This is the first time in over 40 years that Central DeWitt has had a student selected. #gosabers #centraldewittsabers #centraldewittmiddleschool #centraldewittsd #alliowa8thgradehonorband #saberproud

Central Dewitt Saber Athletic Boosters would like your help with one of their biggest fundraisers that benefits ALL of our Sports programs. The 2020 Saber Shootout will be held January 11th for Boys and January 12th for Girls. Please consider volunteering a couple hours of your time for our current and future athletes. Saber Athletic Boosters have donated over $500,000 in the past 10 years to ALL of Central Dewitt Athletic Programs. We are asking for Parents/Adults of Saber Athletes for a couple hours of volunteer time for either Saturday January 11th or Sunday January 12th. We are looking for Volunteers to help with Team Check In, Admissions, Concession Stand and also looking for Baked Goods that are individually wrapped to sell. Thanks in advance for your continued support to Saber Athletics! Click on the link below to Volunteer and to support your Saber Athletes!

https://signup.com/go/fijbJBA

Bring new unwrapped gifts to National Art Honor Society's Gifts for Teens in the high school. If you are lucky enough to have enough to help others please consider donating to this great cause. Bring gifts or donations to the high school office. So far we have only had 8 student donations and 2 staff donations, I know we can come together as a Saber community and help others have a nice holiday!

We will be accepting donations until December 13th!
Anything helps, even if it is just $1.

Thank you, NAHS members Mrs. Dunlavey, Maggie Borota, Grace Pfiefle, Kyleen Irwin, Bethany Witt and Lauryn Ginter
